"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[7153],{37153:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Auth Layer contrasts JWT (stateless) vs Sessions (stateful). Why are JWTs described as \'hard to revoke\' — and what is the standard solution the spec recommends?","options":["JWTs are encrypted with AES-256, making server-side decoding computationally expensive","JWTs are stateless — the server doesn\'t store them. A valid JWT is accepted until expiry even if the user logged out or their account was compromised, because there is nothing server-side to invalidate. The spec uses short-lived access tokens (1h) with revocable refresh tokens stored in Redis","JWT revocation requires restarting all authentication servers simultaneously","JWTs use asymmetric RSA signing which is too slow to check a revocation list on every request"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents the JWT trade-off: \'stateless, scalable, but hard to revoke.\' A JWT signed with a valid secret will pass signature verification until its `exp` timestamp, regardless of whether the user logged out. The spec\'s solution: short-lived access tokens (1 hour TTL) — worst case exposure is 1 hour. Long-lived refresh tokens (30 days) are stored server-side in Redis and can be immediately revoked. On logout: delete the refresh token from Redis. The access token expires naturally.","hint":"Think about what \'stateless\' means — if the server doesn\'t store the token, how can it know the token was invalidated after issuance?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Auth Layer\'s OAuth 2.0 flow diagram includes a `state` parameter passed from client to authorization server and validated on callback. What does this parameter protect against?","options":["It contains the user\'s requested permission scopes (read, write, admin)","It carries the client application\'s version number for compatibility checking","It is a CSRF defense — a random unguessable value the client generates, stores in session/cookie, and validates when the authorization code returns on callback. A mismatch means the callback was forged by a third party","It encodes the user\'s partial session data to avoid a database roundtrip on callback"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents \'OAuth state parameter validated\' in the Production Checklist and lists \'Not validating OAuth state parameter\' as a Common Mistake. Without state validation: an attacker can trick a victim\'s browser into completing an OAuth flow with the attacker\'s authorization code, logging the victim into the attacker\'s account (account takeover). The state value is: generate random UUID → store in session → append to auth URL → validate on callback. The spec also requires PKCE for public clients.","hint":"Consider what happens if a malicious site can craft a callback URL to your OAuth redirect endpoint with their own authorization code — what does `state` prevent?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"What is the critical bug in this password verification function?","code":"async function verifyUserPassword(\\n  inputPassword: string,\\n  storedHash: string\\n): Promise<boolean> {\\n  // Hash the input and compare to stored hash\\n  const inputHash = await bcrypt.hash(inputPassword, 12);\\n  return inputHash === storedHash;\\n}","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["The work factor of 12 is too high and will cause request timeouts in production","The function should use synchronous `bcrypt.hashSync` to prevent race conditions in concurrent requests","`bcrypt.hash()` generates a NEW random salt each call — the same password always produces a different hash. This comparison will always return `false` for valid passwords. Use `bcrypt.compare(inputPassword, storedHash)` which internally extracts the salt from the stored hash before comparing","The function should decode the stored hash from base64 before comparison"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents bcrypt work factor 12 and the `bcrypt.compare()` API. bcrypt embeds a random salt in the stored hash format: `$2b$12$[22-char-salt][31-char-hash]`. `bcrypt.hash(password, 12)` generates a NEW salt and produces a completely different output every time — even for the same password. `bcrypt.compare(password, storedHash)` extracts the salt from `storedHash`, hashes the input with THAT salt, then compares — this is the correct API for verification.","hint":"bcrypt embeds a random salt in the hash output — what happens when you hash the same password twice? Do you get the same result?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"Your system implements refresh token rotation: each use of a refresh token issues a new token and invalidates the old one. An attacker steals a refresh token and uses it first. What should happen when the legitimate user then tries to use their (now-invalidated) token?","options":["The legitimate user gets a new token — their device fingerprint is trusted above the token state","Both requests succeed — the system issues two valid refresh tokens to handle this race condition gracefully","Detecting use of an invalidated (already-rotated) token is a theft signal — the system should immediately revoke ALL refresh tokens for this user family, forcing complete re-authentication and alerting the security team","The legitimate user\'s request is queued and retried after a 30-second backoff period"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents refresh token rotation with \'detect reuse → revoke ALL user tokens.\' This is the \'Refresh Token Reuse Detection\' pattern: each token belongs to a rotation family stored in Redis. When an already-used token is presented, it means the token family was compromised — either the attacker used it first, or the legitimate user did and the attacker has the old token. The only safe response is to invalidate ALL tokens in the family, forcing the user to log in again and cutting off the attacker.","hint":"If someone uses a token that was already rotated (invalidated), what does that tell you about the security of that token family?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Auth Production Checklist, what bcrypt work factor is required for password hashing, and what is the resulting hash duration — and why does that duration matter?","options":["Work factor 8, ~10ms — fast enough for high-traffic login endpoints","Work factor 10, ~100ms — balances security and performance","Work factor ≥ 12, ~250ms — slow enough to make brute-force attacks computationally infeasible (10M passwords/second at factor 8 becomes ~4 passwords/second at factor 12), while still acceptable for login UX","Work factor 16, ~2 seconds — maximum security regardless of user experience impact"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec specifies \'bcrypt/Argon2 work factor ≥ 12\' and \'~250ms per hash.\' The key insight: bcrypt is intentionally slow. At factor 12, an attacker with a GPU cluster can test ~4 passwords/second per hash — making dictionary attacks infeasible. At factor 8, they can test ~40,000/second. The spec also requires \'auth endpoints rate-limited (5 req/min per IP)\' and \'account lockout after failed attempts\' as additional layers, since bcrypt alone is not sufficient.","hint":"Why would you WANT a hash function to be slow? Think about what happens if an attacker steals your hashed password database."}]')}}]);